There is what looks like a copy/paste error in services/github/src/handlers.js that causes Taskcluster to use the wrong filename for custom text output:

https://github.com/taskcluster/taskcluster/blob/master/services/github/src/handlers.js#L549

```
    let textArtifactName = CUSTOM_CHECKRUN_TEXT_ARTIFACT_NAME;
    if (taskDefinition.extra && taskDefinition.extra.github && taskDefinition.extra.github.customCheckRun) {
      textArtifactName =
        taskDefinition.extra.github.customCheckRun.textArtifactName || CUSTOM_CHECKRUN_TEXT_ARTIFACT_NAME;
    }

    let annotationsArtifactName = CUSTOM_CHECKRUN_ANNOTATIONS_ARTIFACT_NAME;
    if (taskDefinition.extra && taskDefinition.extra.github && taskDefinition.extra.github.customCheckRun) {
      textArtifactName =
        taskDefinition.extra.github.customCheckRun.annotationsArtifactName || CUSTOM_CHECKRUN_ANNOTATIONS_ARTIFACT_NAME;
    }
```

The second block overwrites `textArtifactName` rather than `annotationsArtifactName`, so the custom text output ends up being set to either `taskDefinition.extra.github.customCheckRun.annotationsArtifactName` or `CUSTOM_CHECKRUN_ANNOTATIONS_ARTIFACT_NAME`, and overrides don't work at all for `annotationsArtifactName`.

We are adding a lot of things that query a table and call a handler for each row:

```javascript
  await lastFireUtils.getLastFires(
    this.db,
    { hookGroupId: req.params.hookGroupId, hookId: req.params.hookId },
    item => {
      if (item.taskCreateTime > latest.taskCreateTime) {
        latest = item;
      }
    },
  );
```

Let's write a general utility for doing so, similar to `paginatedResults` but designed for internal use.  That should help remove some of the code otherwise appearing in `data.js` and/or `fooUtils.js`.

In #3183, @helfi92 identified an issue where we might "forget" to create a new serialization when adding a column.  Even when adding a new serialization, we want to be sure that values not included in a serialization are NULL.

My vague idea for how to check this in code is to have each serialization declare the columns it consumes:
```javascript
const signingSerializations = [{
  columns: ['col1', 'col2'],
  serialization: row => ..
}, {
  columns: ['col1', 'col2', 'col3'],
  serialization: row => ..
}];
```

Then `calculateSignature` would check that the properties of the `row` it is given match the serialization's columns, or that any unused columns have value `null` in `row` (and allowing a `signature` column).  So

```javascript
// ok
calculateSignature({row: {col1: .., col2: .., col3: ..}, ser: 1, ..});
// fails, col3 is not null and not considered in serialization 0
calculateSignature({row: {col1: .., col2: .., col3: ..}, ser: 0, ..});
// ok, because col3 is null
calculateSignature({row: {col1: .., col2: .., col3: null}, ser: 0, ..});
```

The common structure would be
```javascript
const rows = await db.fns.get_widget(..);
if (!rows.all(row => db.verifySignature({row, signature: row.signature, signingSerializations})) {
  ..
}
```
so if `get_widget()` is changed to `get_widget_and_an_extra_column()`, suddenly `row` will contain an extra column and in cases where that is not null only a serialization that considers that extra column will be allowed.

